-- ============================================================
-- KYBELLA
-- product_id: 0f901fec-5de5-4950-815e-82c3e47cb2ec
-- Active ingredient: Deoxycholic acid (synthetic) 10 mg/mL solution
-- FDA-approved: reduction of moderate-to-severe submental fat (double chin), 2015
-- Very narrow indication: submental only. Injectable. Multiple sessions.
-- NDA 206333
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'd3b83276-ef42-44c4-a083-06386629817d',
  '0f901fec-5de5-4950-815e-82c3e47cb2ec',
  'b51855e7-73a2-498b-b1c4-4fdc739635a2',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'Kybella — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nKybella (deoxycholic acid injection) is the first and only FDA-approved injectable drug for reduction of moderate-to-severe submental fat ("double chin") in adults. Manufactured by Allergan Aesthetics (AbbVie). Active ingredient: synthetic deoxycholic acid 10 mg/mL. [FDA label Kybella NDA 206333]\n\nDeoxycholic acid is a bile acid that naturally occurs in the GI tract where it facilitates dietary fat absorption. Synthetic formulation for submental use is isolated to a specific injection site with no systemic fat reduction effect. [FDA label]\n\n**Critical scope limitation:** Kybella''s FDA approval is specifically and narrowly for **submental fat**. There is no FDA-approved indication for any other body fat deposit. Off-label use for other body sites is described in case literature but is not FDA-endorsed. This is the most anatomically limited indication in the aesthetic injectable category. [FDA label NDA 206333]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nDeoxycholic acid is a **cytolytic agent** — it disrupts cell membrane integrity, causing adipocyte lysis. When injected into the submental fat pad:\n1. Deoxycholic acid penetrates adipocyte cell membranes, disrupting the lipid bilayer\n2. Adipocyte lysis releases lipid contents (triglycerides, fatty acids)\n3. The liberated lipid is processed through the lymphatic system and metabolized\n4. A controlled local inflammatory response follows, eventually resolving with fibrous tissue contraction contributing to additional submental contouring\n\n[FDA label; peer-reviewed: Thuangtong R. J Drugs Dermatol 2010; peer-reviewed: Ascher B. Plast Reconstr Surg 2016]\n\n**Key clinical implication of mechanism:** The inflammatory response is intentional and necessary — it means significant post-injection swelling, firmness, and discomfort is expected for 2-4+ weeks after each treatment. Managing patient expectations about the recovery period is critical to satisfaction. [FDA label]\n\n## FDA-Approved Indication\n\n**Single indication:** Improvement in the appearance of moderate to severe convexity or fullness associated with submental fat in adults. [FDA label NDA 206333, 2015]\n\nNo other FDA-approved indication exists for deoxycholic acid injection in the US. Off-label use for jowl fat, buccal fat, and body fat deposits has been reported in case series but is not FDA-approved. [field practice; note: off-label deoxycholic acid use for non-submental fat should be clearly communicated as off-label]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Ideal candidate profile:**\n- Adults with moderate-to-severe submental fat who are bothered by the appearance of a double chin\n- Patients who have tried diet/exercise without satisfactory submental fat reduction\n- Patients who want a non-surgical option\n- Good skin elasticity in the submental area — significant skin laxity concurrent with fat is a relative contraindication (removing fat may worsen the appearance of lax skin) [FDA label; field practice]\n- Realistic expectations about treatment timeline (multiple sessions, delayed result)\n\n**Poor candidacy signals:**\n- Skin laxity that will worsen cosmetically if submental fat is removed\n- Primary concern is skin laxity rather than fat (different treatment needed)\n- Active infection in the submental area\n- History of dysphagia (risk of marginal mandibular nerve injury from injection)\n- Prior submental surgery or other anatomy-altering procedures that could change injection safety\n- Anticoagulant therapy (bleeding/bruising risk)\n[FDA label; peer-reviewed: Ascher B. Plast Reconstr Surg 2016]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Adverse events [FDA label NDA 206333 — authority rank 1]:**\n- Very common (>50%): injection site edema/swelling, hematoma/bruising, pain, numbness, erythema, induration. The inflammatory response is expected and is part of the mechanism — swelling of 2-4 weeks after each session is normal and should be explicitly pre-communicated. [FDA label]\n- Nerve injury: **marginal mandibular nerve injury** (temporary facial muscle weakness, difficulty smiling) — most important procedural risk. Occurs from injection too close to the mandibular margin. Rate in pivotal trials: 4% per treatment; resolved in most cases. Strict anatomical mapping and adherence to injection grid boundaries are the primary prevention. [FDA label]\n- Dysphagia: temporary difficulty swallowing reported; typically resolves [FDA label]\n- Skin ulceration and necrosis: associated with injection too superficially (intradermal vs. subcutaneous) — the cytolytic mechanism damages any tissue, not just fat. Correct plane confirmation is mandatory. [FDA label]\n\n**Contraindications:** Active infection at injection site. [FDA label]\n\n**Important note:** Deoxycholic acid is cytolytic — it is not tissue-selective despite being lipophilic. Injection into non-fat tissue (dermis, muscle, nerves) causes damage. Strict submental anatomical boundaries must be observed. [FDA label]\n\n## Clinical Outcomes Data\n\nPivotal trials (REFINE-1, REFINE-2): multi-center, placebo-controlled, randomized. Primary endpoints: CR-SMFRS (clinician rating of submental fat) and PR-SMFRS (patient rating). Responder rate (≥1-grade improvement on CR-SMFRS at 12 weeks post last treatment): approximately 68-79% vs. 35% placebo. Significant improvement in patient-reported satisfaction with chin appearance. [FDA label; peer-reviewed: Ascher B. Plast Reconstr Surg 2016]\n\nNumber of sessions: up to 6 sessions (most patients 2-4 sessions), spaced ≥4 weeks apart. [FDA label]\n\n**Gateway posture:** Response rate and number of sessions needed vary with degree of submental fat. For exact dosing, grid spacing, and retreatment protocol, see the Kybella Prescribing Information [FDA/DailyMed →].',
  '391a8d21-d810-4998-94aa-2df7ad347592',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '8e99c839-f93e-4144-bec2-e98725ed971c',
  '0f901fec-5de5-4950-815e-82c3e47cb2ec',
  'b51855e7-73a2-498b-b1c4-4fdc739635a2',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'Kybella — Technique Guide',
  E'## Injection Planes\n\nKybella must be injected into the **subcutaneous fat of the submental zone** — not into skin, muscle, or nerves. The cytolytic mechanism means injection plane accuracy is a safety requirement, not just a technique preference:\n\n- **Plane:** Subcutaneous, within the submental fat pad\n- **Depth confirmation:** The injection should be between the skin surface and the submandibular gland. A "tent test" (lifting skin away from underlying tissue) helps confirm subcutaneous fat thickness and appropriate depth.\n- **Critical boundaries:** Treatment must stay within the marking grid — injections outside the grid risk marginal mandibular nerve injury superiorly, or platysmal injury inferiorly.\n\n[FDA label NDA 206333; peer-reviewed: Ascher B. Plast Reconstr Surg 2016]\n\n## Pre-Treatment Anatomical Mapping\n\n1. Mark the mandibular margin superiorly — injection zone stays ≥1.5 cm below mandibular margin to protect marginal mandibular nerve\n2. Mark the hyoid bone inferiorly — injection zone stays above hyoid level\n3. Identify any palpable enlarged lymph nodes, prior surgical scars, or anatomy-altering findings\n4. Determine submental fat extent horizontally — the injection grid is customized to the fat deposit, not applied uniformly\n\n**Gateway posture:** Exact grid dimensions, spacing between injection sites, and volume per injection point are technique-dependent. Sources describe various grid patterns (1 cm spacing standard in pivotal trials). For exact technique protocol, see the Kybella Prescribing Information and training materials [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Dosing Framework (Range Characterization)\n\n- Volume per injection point: 0.2 mL per injection site [FDA label]\n- Sites per session: up to 50 injection points (depending on fat volume); typically 20-30 for moderate submental fat\n- Total volume per session: 2-10 mL depending on number of injection points\n- Sessions: 2-6 sessions, spaced ≥4 weeks apart; most patients achieve goal in 2-4 sessions\n\n**Gateway pointer:** Total dose and number of sessions should be individualized based on degree of submental fat. See Kybella Prescribing Information [FDA/DailyMed →].\n\n## Technique Notes\n\n- **Patient positioning:** Sitting or supine; clear anatomical landmarks must be visible. Mark patient upright to capture natural submental fat distribution.\n- **Post-injection compression:** Not routinely required, but gentle compression of individual injection sites can minimize hematoma.\n- **Pain management:** Topical anesthesia or ice prior to treatment. The injections are painful; local anesthetic infiltration (separate injection) used by some providers.\n- **Post-treatment counseling:** The inflammatory response (swelling 2-4 weeks, bruising, numbness) must be pre-communicated at consultation to avoid post-treatment dissatisfaction. Many patients interpret expected swelling as a complication without this briefing.\n\n## Treatment Planning\n\n- Initial assessment: determine degree of submental fat; assess skin laxity; rule out submental anatomy that contraindicates treatment (lymph nodes, prior surgery)\n- Concurrent skin laxity treatment: if mild-to-moderate laxity present, consider pairing with skin tightening (Ultherapy, Morpheus8, Sofwave) at the appropriate treatment interval to address both fat and laxity\n- Retreatment interval: minimum 4 weeks between sessions\n- Assessment timing: evaluate result at ≥12 weeks after last treatment for final outcome assessment\n\n## Combination Sequencing\n\nKybella for submental fat reduction + skin tightening device (Ultherapy, Sofwave, Morpheus8) for concurrent submental laxity is a common and clinically logical combination. The sequencing (concurrent vs. staged) is a clinical judgment. Many providers prefer to reduce fat first (Kybella) and then reassess laxity at follow-up before adding a tightening treatment. [field practice — sources differ on sequencing preference]',
  '2227735b-c23d-438c-a97c-029987d81859',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  'ee1ae5bd-dd8c-44d8-92c3-ab84998228f8',
  '0f901fec-5de5-4950-815e-82c3e47cb2ec',
  'b51855e7-73a2-498b-b1c4-4fdc739635a2',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'Kybella — Patient Education',
  E'## What It Does for You\n\nKybella is the only FDA-approved injectable specifically designed to eliminate submental fat — the fat beneath your chin that creates a double chin appearance. It''s the non-surgical option for a concern that diet and exercise often can''t fully resolve (submental fat has a genetic component for many people and tends to be diet-resistant).\n\nKybella''s active ingredient, deoxycholic acid, is a synthetic version of a molecule your body naturally produces in the digestive system. When injected into the fat under your chin, it breaks down fat cells permanently. Once those fat cells are destroyed, they cannot store or accumulate fat again.\n\nThe result: a defined jawline and chin profile. Permanent fat cell destruction means you don''t need ongoing treatment to maintain the result — once you''ve achieved your goal, most patients don''t need more.\n\n## Permanent Fat Cell Elimination\n\nThis is Kybella''s core value proposition and its distinction from temporary treatments. Deoxycholic acid causes permanent destruction of fat cells (adipocytes). Your body''s lymphatic system then processes and eliminates the lipids from the destroyed cells. The cells themselves do not regenerate.\n\nFor patients who have been frustrated by the persistence of their double chin through significant weight loss, Kybella targets the structural cause — the fat compartment itself — not the symptoms.\n\n**Important note:** While fat cells are permanently destroyed, Kybella is not a substitute for weight management. Significant weight gain after treatment can cause remaining fat cells to enlarge. The goal is contouring at a stable weight.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**During treatment:** Kybella is administered as a series of small injections in the mapped treatment zone under your chin. Your injector will mark the treatment area and perform multiple injections in a grid pattern across the fat deposit. Each session takes approximately 15-20 minutes.\n\n**After treatment (this is important to know in advance):** Kybella''s mechanism creates an intentional inflammatory response as part of how it works. For 2-4 weeks after each session, you will have significant swelling, firmness, and possible bruising under your chin. This is **expected and normal** — it is your body responding to the fat cell elimination. Most patients plan for some social downtime after each session, especially the first treatment when the response tends to be most pronounced.\n\n**Number of sessions:** Most patients need 2-4 sessions, spaced at least 4 weeks apart. Some patients see significant improvement after 2 sessions; others require more to reach their goal.\n\n**Final result:** Full results are assessed at 12 weeks after your last treatment as swelling fully resolves. Most patients see meaningful, visible improvement in chin definition and profile.\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nThe value of permanent fat cell elimination is that it is a one-time investment toward a permanent structural change. For patients who have long been bothered by their double chin, this addresses the root cause rather than masking it. The swelling and multi-session protocol are the cost of that permanence — a trade that most patients readily accept once they understand what they''re paying for.\n\n**Value consideration:** Because the result is permanent, the cost-per-year calculation is favorable compared to treatments requiring ongoing maintenance. After completing your treatment course, you generally do not need to return for submental fat reduction.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nDouble chin appearance has two components: fat and skin laxity. Kybella addresses the fat. If skin laxity is also present under your chin, your injector may recommend combining Kybella with a skin tightening treatment (such as Ultherapy, Sofwave, or Morpheus8) for a complete result. Your injector will assess your specific anatomy and recommend the right combination for you.\n\n## Maintenance\n\nOnce your goal is achieved, maintenance sessions are not typically needed for the fat itself — the fat cells are permanently eliminated. Ongoing weight maintenance and healthy lifestyle support the long-term result. If you have concurrent skin laxity that was addressed, maintenance for that component follows the schedule of whichever device was used.',
  '312e452e-1e7d-4aef-a1fa-d113da6b5273',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '315f20f8-c4b7-45db-ae29-546780e681ed',
  '0f901fec-5de5-4950-815e-82c3e47cb2ec',
  'b51855e7-73a2-498b-b1c4-4fdc739635a2',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'Kybella — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"Is the swelling normal?"**\nYes — the swelling is expected and is actually part of how Kybella works. The deoxycholic acid creates an inflammatory response as it breaks down fat cells, and this manifests as significant swelling, firmness, and sometimes bruising under your chin for 2-4 weeks after each session. Knowing this in advance (and planning for it) is the key to a satisfying experience. The swelling is temporary and reflects that the treatment is working.\n\n**"How many sessions will I need?"**\nMost patients need 2-4 sessions, spaced at least 4 weeks apart. The exact number depends on the volume of submental fat. Your provider will assess at your consultation and at each follow-up. You will see progressive improvement across sessions as the fat is reduced and your body eliminates the destroyed cells.\n\n**"Will it come back?"**\nFat cells destroyed by Kybella do not regenerate. The fat that is treated is permanently eliminated. Significant weight gain after treatment can cause remaining fat cells (in other areas or any remaining submental cells) to enlarge, but the cells specifically destroyed do not return. Maintaining a stable weight supports the longevity of the result.\n\n**"Does it hurt?"**\nKybella injections cause a burning sensation during and briefly after the injection, which subsides quickly. Your provider may apply topical anesthesia or ice beforehand. The post-treatment swelling and firmness are generally not painful — more of a pressure sensation.\n\n**"What about the skin under my chin — will it sag?"**\nThis is an important question. If you have significant skin laxity as well as fat, removing the fat alone may worsen the appearance of loose skin. Your injector will assess whether skin tightening treatment should be combined with Kybella or done afterward to achieve the best result for your anatomy.\n\n**"Can it be used anywhere else on my body?"**\nKybella''s FDA approval is specifically for submental fat — under the chin — only. Off-label use in other areas has been described, but those uses are outside the FDA-approved indication and carry different risk profiles. Your provider can discuss what is appropriate for your specific concerns.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"The swelling sounds like too much downtime."**\nThe inflammatory response (swelling) is the mechanism — it''s how the fat cells are eliminated, and it''s temporary. Most patients plan for some social downtime for 1-2 weeks after their first treatment when swelling is most noticeable. After that, normal activity is fine. The trade is temporary swelling for permanent fat cell elimination.\n\n**"Multiple sessions sounds like a lot of appointments."**\nKybella is a treatment course, not a lifetime commitment. Once you complete your 2-4 sessions and achieve your goal, you generally do not need to return for this concern. Compare this to treatments requiring ongoing maintenance every 6-12 months — Kybella''s total appointment count is often lower over the long term.',
  '312e452e-1e7d-4aef-a1fa-d113da6b5273',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '46d4c9d0-8f60-48f7-b4f1-cb1540e1fdf7',
  '0f901fec-5de5-4950-815e-82c3e47cb2ec',
  'b51855e7-73a2-498b-b1c4-4fdc739635a2',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'Kybella — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\nKybella holds a unique, narrow position as the **only FDA-approved injectable for submental fat reduction**. Its differentiation is defined by both its mechanism and its scope:\n\n- **Mechanism uniqueness:** Cytolysis via deoxycholic acid is distinct from all other injectable fat reduction approaches. It is not cryolipolysis, not lipolysis (laser/RF), not suction lipoplasty.\n- **Indication scope:** Submental fat ONLY — the narrowest anatomical indication in the body contouring category. This is both a limitation (no other areas) and a strength (maximum clinical specificity for this one indication).\n- **Permanence:** Fat cell destruction vs. temporary reduction — directly competing with surgical chin liposuction on permanence grounds, with a non-surgical risk profile.\n\nVersus CoolSculpting: CoolSculpting (cryolipolysis) is FDA-cleared for submental fat AND multiple body areas. For submental specifically, Kybella vs. CoolSculpting is a valid clinical comparison — both are non-surgical, both reduce submental fat, both require multiple sessions. Key differences: Kybella is injectable (multiple needle injections vs. applicator), Kybella swelling is more pronounced post-session. CoolSculpting has a broader body application. Provider and patient preference guides choice. No head-to-head RCT. [field practice; both FDA-cleared/approved for submental]\n\nVersus surgical chin liposuction: Surgical liposuction provides more precise fat removal, often in fewer sessions, but requires anesthesia and carries surgical risks. Kybella targets patients who want to avoid surgery. [field practice]\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\n**Deoxycholic acid cytolysis:**\n- Deoxycholic acid (DCA) is an endogenous bile salt; synthetic formulation is identical to bile-derived DCA\n- DCA disrupts cell membrane phospholipid bilayers — not fat-specific in mechanism but fat-selective in practice when injected subcutaneously (the predominant cell type at the injection site is adipocyte)\n- **Important:** DCA is cytolytic to any cell type at the injection concentration. The safety of the treatment depends on precise subcutaneous injection to avoid dermal, neural, or muscular tissue.\n- Post-lysis: inflammatory cascade (macrophage recruitment, lymphatic clearance of lipid debris), followed by fibrotic contraction contributing to submental tightening\n\n[FDA label NDA 206333; peer-reviewed: Thuangtong R. J Drugs Dermatol 2010]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\n**REFINE-1 and REFINE-2 pivotal trials:**\n- Multi-center, double-blind, placebo-controlled, randomized\n- N: 1022 (REFINE-1) and 507 (REFINE-2) subjects\n- Primary endpoints: CR-SMFRS (≥1 grade improvement) and PR-SMFRS (≥1 grade improvement) at 12 weeks post last treatment\n- Results: Responder rate ~68-79% for Kybella vs. ~35% for placebo on CR-SMFRS; similar pattern on PR-SMFRS\n- Safety: marginal mandibular nerve injury 4% per treatment (all resolved in trial population)\n[FDA label NDA 206333; peer-reviewed: Ascher B. Plast Reconstr Surg 2016]\n\n**Key publications:**\n- Ascher B et al. Plast Reconstr Surg 2016 — REFINE trial 12-month outcomes\n- Thuangtong R et al. J Drugs Dermatol 2010 — DCA mechanism characterization\n- Rotunda AM et al. Dermatol Surg 2004 — Deoxycholic acid injection for submental fat (early data)\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Parameter | Kybella | CoolSculpting Elite | Surgical Liposuction |\n|-----------|---------|--------------------|-----------------------|\n| Mechanism | Chemical cytolysis (DCA) | Cryolipolysis | Mechanical suction |\n| FDA status | Approved (submental only) | Cleared (multiple areas incl. submental) | Standard surgical procedure |\n| Permanence | Fat cells destroyed | Fat cells destroyed | Fat cells removed |\n| Sessions | 2-6, ≥4 weeks apart | 1-2 per area | Single surgical procedure |\n| Recovery | 2-4 weeks swelling/bruising | 1-2 weeks mild bruising/numbness | 1-3 weeks surgical recovery |\n| Submental applicability | Excellent (specific FDA approval) | Good (CoolMini/CoolSculpting cleared) | Excellent |\n| Body areas beyond submental | Not FDA-approved | Multiple cleared areas | Unlimited |\n\nGateway posture: comparison data is from respective product labeling and published outcomes; head-to-head RCT between Kybella and CoolSculpting for submental fat does not exist in current literature.',
  '40245613-20c1-45b4-b20c-2ce90e83d0b3',
  'draft', 1
);

-- ============================================================
-- COOLSCULPTING ELITE
-- product_id: 694ea839-cf8f-4a17-b838-2588674c792f
-- Active mechanism: Cryolipolysis (controlled cooling of subcutaneous fat)
-- FDA-cleared: multiple body areas for non-invasive fat reduction
-- SAFETY FLOOR: PAH (Paradoxical Adipose Hyperplasia) — must appear in clinical summary
-- 510k: device; current platform is CoolSculpting Elite with DualSculpting capability
-- ============================================================

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '4d3a566b-9c9f-404a-ab18-d912cfa1c849',
  '694ea839-cf8f-4a17-b838-2588674c792f',
  'd72803ce-814f-4905-8ce4-3d44323e9503',
  'clinical', 'clinical_summary', 'provider',
  'CoolSculpting Elite — Clinical Summary',
  E'## Product Identity\n\nCoolSculpting Elite is the current-generation cryolipolysis platform manufactured by AbbVie Aesthetics. It delivers controlled cooling to selectively reduce subcutaneous fat in FDA-cleared body areas. The Elite platform features redesigned applicators with increased fat contact area (~18% more vs. prior generation) and DualSculpting capability (two applicators simultaneously). [FDA 510k clearance; manufacturer IFU CoolSculpting Elite]\n\n**Mechanism class:** Cryolipolysis — selective fat crystallization via controlled cooling. The core technology has been FDA-cleared since 2010; the Elite platform is the latest generation. [FDA 510k clearance database]\n\n## Mechanism of Action\n\nCryolipolysis is based on the observation that adipocytes are more susceptible to cold-induced injury than surrounding tissue (skin, nerves, muscles) at specific temperature ranges (-9°C to -11°C is the clinically effective range for fat crystallization). The mechanism:\n\n1. The applicator delivers controlled cooling to the targeted subcutaneous fat depot\n2. At approximately -9°C to -11°C, adipocyte intracellular lipids begin to crystallize (fat freezes at a higher temperature than water-based tissue)\n3. Crystallized lipids rupture the adipocyte cell membrane\n4. An inflammatory cascade (cryolipolysis-induced panniculitis) clears the debris via macrophage activity over 4-12 weeks\n5. Net result: progressive reduction in fat layer thickness as debris is processed\n\n[FDA 510k clearance; peer-reviewed: Dierickx CC. Lasers Surg Med 2013; peer-reviewed: Manstein D. Lasers Surg Med 2008 — foundational cryolipolysis mechanism paper]\n\n## FDA-Cleared Treatment Areas\n\nCoolSculpting has received FDA clearance for multiple body areas. The Elite platform adds redesigned C-Cup applicators for improved contact:\n\n- **Abdomen** (flanks/love handles): FDA-cleared [510k]\n- **Flanks** (lateral abdomen): FDA-cleared [510k]\n- **Thighs** (inner and outer): FDA-cleared [510k]\n- **Submental area** (double chin): FDA-cleared (CoolMini applicator) [510k]\n- **Upper arms**: FDA-cleared [510k]\n- **Bra fat / back fat**: FDA-cleared [510k]\n- **Banana roll** (posterior thigh below buttock): FDA-cleared [510k]\n\n**Gateway posture:** Clearance status by body area — confirm current cleared indication list with the manufacturer for the most current 510k clearance scope. Clinical outcomes vary by area; not all areas show equal response rates. [FDA 510k; manufacturer IFU]\n\n## Candidacy\n\n**Ideal candidate profile:**\n- Adults within approximately 30 lbs of their goal weight with discrete, localized fat deposits that are diet-resistant\n- Patients who want non-invasive fat reduction without surgery or significant downtime\n- Those with adequate subcutaneous fat thickness to fill applicator (minimum fat pinch of approximately 2.5 cm depending on applicator)\n- Realistic expectations: CoolSculpting is a body contouring tool, not a weight loss treatment — appropriate patients see it as the final step to address stubborn localized fat deposits\n\n**Poor candidacy signals:**\n- Cryoglobulinemia, cold agglutinin disease, or paroxysmal cold hemoglobinuria — absolute contraindications (cold sensitivity conditions) [FDA label/IFU]\n- Raynaud''s disease or significant cold sensitivity [IFU]\n- Inadequate subcutaneous fat at target site (insufficient tissue for applicator)\n- Active or recent skin conditions, wounds, or treatment scars at target site\n- Hernia at treatment site\n- Patients expecting weight loss (visceral fat is not treated; the treatment is contouring, not weight management)\n- Very obese patients where the target fat is visceral rather than subcutaneous\n[FDA IFU; peer-reviewed: Ingargiola MJ. Plast Reconstr Surg 2015]\n\n## Safety Profile\n\n**Common adverse events (expected, transient) [FDA 510k/IFU — authority rank 1]:**\n- During treatment: intense cold, aching, stinging, cramping at applicator site\n- Post-treatment (hours to days): redness, swelling, bruising, firmness, temporary numbness, tingling — all expected as part of the panniculitis response\n- Late firmness: 1-4 weeks after treatment, treated area typically feels firm/hard as the inflammatory process peaks; resolves over 4-12 weeks\n\n**SAFETY FLOOR — Paradoxical Adipose Hyperplasia (PAH):**\nPAH is a rare but serious adverse event that MUST be disclosed to patients prior to treatment. It involves **paradoxical increase in subcutaneous fat volume** at the treated site rather than reduction, appearing approximately 2-5 months after treatment. The mechanism is not fully understood — hypothesized to involve a reactive adipogenesis response triggered by cryolipolysis in susceptible individuals.\n\n- **Incidence:** Originally reported as very rare (~1/20,000 treatments); subsequent real-world data suggests higher frequency in certain populations (~1/138 in some published analyses). [peer-reviewed: Singh SM. JAMA Dermatol 2019]\n- **Presentation:** A painless, well-defined enlargement of the treatment area that does not respond to additional cryolipolysis. Characteristically defined as the "stick of butter" sign — a discrete, firm, enlarged fat mass matching the applicator shape.\n- **Management:** Surgical liposuction is the only effective treatment. PAH does not resolve spontaneously. [FDA Safety Communication 2019; peer-reviewed: Singh SM. JAMA Dermatol 2019]\n- **Risk factors:** The incidence appears to be higher in male patients and possibly with certain applicators. Current data does not allow precise individual risk prediction.\n- **Disclosure requirement:** PAH must be discussed at consultation and documented in informed consent. [FDA Safety Communication on Rare Adverse Effect of Cryolipolysis, 2019]\n\n**Other rare adverse events:** Subcutaneous tissue changes (hyperpigmentation, irregular contour, prolonged numbness). [FDA IFU]\n\n**Contraindications [FDA IFU — authority rank 1]:** Cryoglobulinemia, cold agglutinin disease, paroxysmal cold hemoglobinuria. Active skin conditions or lesions at treatment site.\n\n## Clinical Outcomes Data\n\nMeta-analysis and systematic review evidence: average fat reduction of approximately 10-25% of subcutaneous fat layer thickness per treatment session. Number of sessions for goal reduction: typically 1-2 per area, reassessed at 4-12 weeks. [peer-reviewed: Ingargiola MJ. Plast Reconstr Surg 2015 — systematic review; peer-reviewed: Dierickx CC. Lasers Surg Med 2013]\n\n**Gateway posture:** Fat reduction percentage and number of sessions vary significantly by body site, applicator type, individual fat layer thickness and composition, and patient metabolism. For specific clearance scope and protocol, see CoolSculpting Elite IFU and current 510k clearance documentation [FDA 510k database →].',
  '2dcf1b98-2f00-4205-8fab-5e8b58175526',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '111cf2c8-67d3-4e53-bee0-9d689f98752f',
  '694ea839-cf8f-4a17-b838-2588674c792f',
  'd72803ce-814f-4905-8ce4-3d44323e9503',
  'clinical', 'technique_guide', 'provider',
  'CoolSculpting Elite — Technique Guide',
  E'## Applicator Selection\n\nCoolSculpting Elite uses a family of applicators matched to body site and fat volume. Correct applicator selection is the primary technique variable:\n\n- **CoolAdvantage C-Cup applicators (Elite-specific):** Enhanced vacuum cup design; covers approximately 18% more surface area vs. prior generation. Used for abdomen, flanks, inner thighs, outer thighs.\n- **CoolMini:** Smaller applicator for submental and axillary fat (smaller deposits requiring focused application)\n- **CoolSmooth PRO:** Flat applicator for non-pinchable areas (outer thighs, male flank fat)\n- **CoolFit:** Narrower for inner thigh placement\n\nApplicator choice is guided by: deposit size, pinch test (minimum ~2 cm for cup applicators), anatomical contour, and fat distribution pattern. Incorrect applicator sizing leads to suboptimal coverage and contour irregularities. [manufacturer IFU; field practice consensus]\n\n## Treatment Zones and Planning\n\n**Mapping:** Mark treatment zones based on the fat deposit — not anatomical landmarks. The treatment area should correspond to the visually and palpably distinct fat deposit the patient is treating. Over-marking (treating adjacent skin without fat) does not improve results and increases PAH risk zone.\n\n**DualSculpting:** CoolSculpting Elite supports simultaneous dual applicator treatment, reducing total session time. Applicator pairs must be clinically appropriate for concurrent treatment of the specific anatomy.\n\n**Session planning:**\n- Mark treatment cycles needed to cover the fat deposit\n- Assess whether 1-2 cycles per area per session is sufficient or if staged sessions are needed\n- Document baseline with standardized photography from all relevant angles\n\n[FDA IFU; manufacturer CoolSculpting Elite treatment guide]\n\n## Treatment Parameters\n\n**Gateway posture:** Cooling intensity, treatment duration, and cycle count are device-set parameters per the FDA-cleared protocol for each applicator/body-area combination. CoolSculpting Elite does not allow operator override of core treatment parameters (temperature, time). Clinical judgment applies to applicator selection, treatment area mapping, and cycle count. For exact protocol parameters by applicator, see the IFU [FDA 510k/IFU →].\n\n## Post-Treatment Massage\n\nImmediately after applicator removal, the treated area should be massaged for approximately 2 minutes. Clinical evidence suggests that this post-treatment massage improves fat reduction outcomes by approximately 68% compared to no massage (based on internal CoolSculpting data). This is a standard and important protocol step. [manufacturer clinical data; peer-reviewed: Boey GE. J Drugs Dermatol 2014]\n\n## Treatment Planning\n\n- Initial consultation: assess areas, applicator fit, medical history (screen for cold sensitivity contraindications), candidacy for CoolSculpting vs. alternatives (Kybella for submental, liposuction for large volumes)\n- Cycle planning: most areas require 1-2 treatment cycles; abdomen may require 2-4 cycles for adequate coverage\n- Retreatment interval: minimum 4-8 weeks for result assessment; fat reduction continues for up to 12 weeks post-treatment\n- Combination consideration: skin laxity concurrent with fat may benefit from skin tightening (Morpheus8, Ultherapy) staged separately\n\n## PAH Risk Reduction Protocol\n\nWhile individual risk for PAH cannot be predicted, best practice protocol includes:\n- Complete PAH disclosure and documentation at consultation\n- Male patients may warrant additional discussion of PAH risk (higher incidence in some reports)\n- Avoid treating areas with inadequate fat volume for the selected applicator\n- Document each treatment area and applicator used for traceability if PAH occurs\n[FDA Safety Communication 2019; field practice consensus]',
  'c9fb67b3-6122-4a9a-8116-16872d269daf',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '45a71dfc-2dd3-4879-a360-ba88b3ca3442',
  '694ea839-cf8f-4a17-b838-2588674c792f',
  'd72803ce-814f-4905-8ce4-3d44323e9503',
  'sales_education', 'patient_education', 'patient',
  'CoolSculpting Elite — Patient Education',
  E'## What It Does for You\n\nCoolSculpting Elite is the latest generation of the most well-known non-invasive body contouring treatment in the world — and the one with the most FDA-cleared treatment areas. It uses precisely controlled cold temperatures to freeze and permanently eliminate fat cells from specific areas of your body, without surgery and without significant recovery time.\n\nHere''s the science in plain language: fat cells freeze at a slightly warmer temperature than surrounding tissue (like skin, muscle, and nerves). CoolSculpting takes advantage of this difference — it cools your skin to a temperature that destroys fat cells but leaves everything else unharmed. Over the following weeks, your body naturally processes and eliminates the destroyed fat cells. The result is a measurable, visible reduction in the fat layer in the treated area.\n\n## FDA-Cleared for Multiple Body Areas\n\nCoolSculpting is one of the most versatile non-invasive body contouring options available because it''s been cleared for treatment across many areas:\n\n- Abdomen\n- Love handles / flanks\n- Inner and outer thighs\n- Submental area (double chin)\n- Upper arms\n- Bra fat / back fat\n- Banana roll (below the buttock)\n\nThis versatility means a comprehensive contouring plan can be addressed in a single practice, often in a single appointment.\n\n## What to Expect\n\n**During treatment:** An applicator is placed on the treatment area, drawing the tissue in with gentle suction and applying cold. You will feel intense cold, pressure, and possibly tingling or aching for the first few minutes — after which the area typically becomes numb and the treatment is comfortable. Each applicator cycle takes approximately 35-75 minutes. The Elite platform can run two applicators simultaneously (DualSculpting), which cuts your total time in half for bilateral treatments.\n\n**Right after:** The treated area will look red and may feel firm and temporarily numb immediately after the applicator is removed. Your provider will massage the treated area — this step improves results. Most people return to normal activities the same day.\n\n**The weeks after:** Fat reduction is gradual. The inflammatory process of eliminating destroyed fat cells takes 4-12 weeks. You will see progressive improvement over this period. Final results are typically assessed at 3 months after treatment.\n\n**How many sessions?** Many patients see their goal result with 1-2 sessions per area. Some areas or patients with more fat to address need additional cycles or a second treatment session assessed at 3 months.\n\n## Benefit Framing\n\nCoolSculpting is for the patient who is at or near their healthy weight and has specific, localized areas of fat that won''t budge with diet and exercise. These areas often have a genetic component and are genuinely different from global fat — they respond differently to metabolic signals. CoolSculpting targets the structural cause (the fat cells themselves) with permanent results.\n\n**Value:** The fat cells eliminated by CoolSculpting do not regenerate. Maintaining a stable weight after treatment preserves the result long-term — no ongoing maintenance needed for the eliminated fat.\n\n## An Important Safety Note: PAH\n\nThere is a rare but real side effect called Paradoxical Adipose Hyperplasia (PAH) that your provider will discuss with you before treatment. In rare cases, CoolSculpting can cause the treated area to develop more fat volume instead of less — the opposite of the intended outcome. PAH appears gradually over 2-5 months after treatment. If it occurs, surgical intervention is needed to address it.\n\nPAH is rare, but because it is a material risk, your provider will review it with you, answer your questions, and document the discussion. Being well-informed about this possibility is part of making a good decision about whether CoolSculpting is right for you.\n\n## Combination Therapy\n\nCoolSculpting addresses fat. If skin laxity is part of your concern (loose or sagging skin in the treatment area), your provider may recommend combining CoolSculpting with a skin tightening treatment. Common pairings include Morpheus8 (RF microneedling for skin tightening and tissue remodeling) or Ultherapy/Sofwave (ultrasound skin tightening). Timing and sequencing will depend on your provider''s assessment of your specific anatomy.\n\n## Maintenance\n\nThe fat cells eliminated are permanently gone. Future weight gain will affect remaining fat cells (which can enlarge), but the treated cells themselves do not return. Most patients who maintain stable weight after treatment retain their results long-term without additional CoolSculpting sessions.',
  '7d82c7c6-abb1-4852-abf0-e7290ac4ac98',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '59540a69-f7b0-47f5-af5f-9ee9eda5fa06',
  '694ea839-cf8f-4a17-b838-2588674c792f',
  'd72803ce-814f-4905-8ce4-3d44323e9503',
  'sales_education', 'faq', 'patient',
  'CoolSculpting Elite — FAQ',
  E'## Common Questions\n\n**"Is it really permanent?"**\nYes. Cryolipolysis destroys fat cells. The destroyed cells are eliminated by your body''s immune system over 4-12 weeks and do not regenerate. The fat cells treated are permanently gone. However, remaining fat cells in the body can still expand with significant weight gain — CoolSculpting is body contouring, not a weight loss treatment. Maintaining a stable weight maximizes the long-term result.\n\n**"How much fat will it remove?"**\nClinical studies show an average reduction of approximately 10-25% in the treated fat layer per session. Results vary based on the area treated, the volume of fat, and individual response. It is a body contouring treatment designed for localized, stubborn fat deposits — not a large-volume fat removal method. Your provider will help you understand what result is realistic for your specific anatomy.\n\n**"Does it hurt?"**\nDuring treatment: the first 5-10 minutes feel intensely cold, with possible aching, stinging, or cramping as the area cools. After that, the area numbs and most patients find the rest of the treatment comfortable (many read, watch videos, or nap). After treatment: the area may be tender, firm, and temporarily numb. These sensations resolve over days to weeks.\n\n**"Can it treat my stomach AND my love handles at the same appointment?"**\nYes — the CoolSculpting Elite platform supports DualSculpting (two applicators running simultaneously), meaning bilateral areas or multiple areas can be treated in a single appointment. Your provider will plan the most efficient treatment session for your specific goals.\n\n**"What is PAH and how worried should I be?"**\nPAH (Paradoxical Adipose Hyperplasia) is a rare but real adverse effect where the treated area develops increased fat volume instead of decreased volume. It appears 2-5 months after treatment and requires surgery to address. The incidence is rare but has been reported more frequently than initially understood in early safety data. Your provider will discuss PAH with you before treatment and document this disclosure. The appropriate response is to be informed, not alarmed — rare but real risks deserve honest discussion, and your provider is prepared to help you understand whether CoolSculpting is right for you.\n\n**"Will I see results right away?"**\nNo — fat elimination is a gradual process. The treated fat cells are destroyed at the session, but your body processes and eliminates them over 4-12 weeks. You will see progressive improvement over this period. Final results are assessed at approximately 3 months post-treatment.\n\n## Objection Reframes\n\n**"I''m worried about the PAH risk."**\nPAH is rare, and being informed about it demonstrates that your practice is being thorough, not that this is a dangerous treatment. Serious adverse events from CoolSculpting in general are uncommon. Your provider will review your candidacy carefully and can help you evaluate whether your specific anatomy and health history represent any additional risk factors. Knowing the risks means you can make an informed decision.\n\n**"I''ve heard results vary a lot."**\nCoolSculpting works consistently for the right candidate — someone with localized, pinchable fat deposits in FDA-cleared areas at a stable weight. Results are most dramatic for patients who are well-selected for the treatment. If you''re within 20-30 lbs of your goal weight with specific fat deposits that won''t respond to diet and exercise, the clinical evidence supports meaningful improvement. For patients using it as a weight-loss tool, results will disappoint regardless of technique.',
  '7d82c7c6-abb1-4852-abf0-e7290ac4ac98',
  'draft', 1
);

INSERT INTO agent_reference_docs (
  id, offering_id, category_id, lens, doc_type, audience, title, content_md,
  extends_doc_id, status, version
) VALUES (
  '15452200-5aaa-4457-b1b1-3747a27f5d2f',
  '694ea839-cf8f-4a17-b838-2588674c792f',
  'd72803ce-814f-4905-8ce4-3d44323e9503',
  'deep_product', 'deep_dive_playbook', 'provider',
  'CoolSculpting Elite — Deep Dive Playbook',
  E'## Differentiation\n\nCoolSculpting Elite is the only cryolipolysis platform with multi-area FDA clearance and the most validated non-invasive fat reduction technology by published evidence volume. Key differentiators:\n\n1. **Multi-area clearance:** 7+ FDA-cleared body areas; broadest non-invasive fat reduction indication set\n2. **DualSculpting:** Simultaneous dual applicator — efficiency differentiator vs. single-applicator devices\n3. **Applicator redesign (Elite):** C-Cup design increases fat engagement area by ~18%; improved patient outcomes data vs. prior generation\n4. **Evidence base:** CoolSculpting has the largest body of published evidence among non-invasive fat reduction devices by study count\n\nVersus Kybella (submental only): For submental fat specifically, both are valid. CoolSculpting''s CoolMini vs. Kybella for submental — no head-to-head RCT. CoolSculpting has external device application vs. Kybella''s multiple injections. Different recovery profiles (CoolSculpting: swelling/numbness 1-2 weeks vs. Kybella: significant swelling 2-4 weeks). Practice offering often includes both for patient choice.\n\nVersus HIFU body (high-intensity focused ultrasound for fat): Limited comparative data. CoolSculpting has more robust evidence base. Not the same modality.\n\nVersus surgical liposuction: Liposuction removes larger fat volumes in single session; requires anesthesia; surgical risk. CoolSculpting appropriate for mild-moderate localized fat; non-surgical profile. Different patient populations.\n\n## Mechanism Detail\n\n**Cryolipolysis physics:**\n- Adipocyte lipid crystallization temperature: approximately -9°C to -11°C (lipids crystallize at warmer temperatures than water-based tissue due to different phase transition properties)\n- Surrounding tissue (skin, nerves): water-based, does not crystallize at these temperatures\n- Controlled cooling cycle: device maintains precise temperature range; active skin temperature monitoring prevents unsafe surface cooling\n- Post-crystallization: adipocyte membrane rupture → lipid release → panniculitis (cryolipolysis-induced) → macrophage clearance of lipid debris → net reduction in fat layer volume\n\n**Timeline:** Fat cell death is immediate at the session. Inflammatory clearance proceeds over 4-12 weeks (peak inflammatory phase 2-4 weeks; maximal visible fat reduction 2-3 months post-treatment). [peer-reviewed: Manstein D. Lasers Surg Med 2008 — foundational; peer-reviewed: Dierickx CC. Lasers Surg Med 2013]\n\n**PAH mechanism hypothesis:**\n- Proposed: in susceptible individuals, cryolipolysis may trigger a stimulus for reactive adipogenesis (adipocyte proliferation) rather than clearance\n- The paradoxical response appears at approximately 2-5 months\n- Risk factors: male sex (possibly), specific applicator types (debated in literature)\n- Mechanistic certainty: LOW — PAH mechanism is not fully understood; no validated predictive test exists\n[peer-reviewed: Singh SM. JAMA Dermatol 2019; FDA Safety Communication 2019]\n\n## Evidence Summary\n\n**Foundational science:**\n- Manstein D et al. Lasers Surg Med 2008 — Cryolipolysis: controlled cooling of subcutaneous fat; foundational mechanism paper\n- Dierickx CC et al. Lasers Surg Med 2013 — Safety and efficacy of cryolipolysis; large clinical series\n\n**Systematic review:**\n- Ingargiola MJ et al. Plast Reconstr Surg 2015 — Meta-analysis: mean fat reduction ~10-25% per cycle; adverse event profile consistent across studies\n\n**PAH:**\n- Singh SM et al. JAMA Dermatol 2019 — Estimated incidence 1/138 treatments in a large single-center series (higher than initial estimates); male sex as risk factor\n- FDA Safety Communication, September 2019 — PAH added to device labeling\n\n**Elite platform:**\n- Manufacturer clinical data: C-Cup design 18% more fat contact area; internal studies referenced in product materials (not independently peer-reviewed at time of compilation)\n\n## Comparison Anchors\n\n| Parameter | CoolSculpting Elite | Kybella | Morpheus8 |\n|-----------|--------------------|---------|-----------|\n| Mechanism | Cryolipolysis | Chemical cytolysis | RF microneedling |\n| Primary effect | Fat reduction | Fat reduction (submental) | Skin tightening + remodeling |\n| FDA scope | 7+ body areas | Submental only | Skin/tissue (not fat primary) |\n| Sessions | 1-2 per area | 2-6 (submental) | 3-4 per area |\n| PAH risk | Yes (rare) | No | No |\n| Recovery | 1-2 weeks mild | 2-4 weeks swelling | 1-3 days (device-dependent) |\n| Skin laxity | Does not address | Does not address | Addresses directly |\n\nGateway posture: comparison values are from respective FDA labels, 510k clearances, and published literature; head-to-head comparative studies do not exist across these modalities. Product selection is a clinical judgment based on patient anatomy, concerns, and goals.',
  '22139ec3-60b5-40fe-903e-ed1ec1595d97',
  'draft', 1
);
